                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d951">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">892.61317/8–1845</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Chief of the Division of Southeast Asian
                        Affairs</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Moffat</hi>) <hi rend="italic">of a
                        Conversation With the Secretary of the Thai Legation</hi> (<hi rend="italic"
                        >Sanasen</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-08-18">August 18,
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>In the course of a conversation I expressed as my purely personal view that it
                    might be a wise political step for Thailand to offer a substantial amount of the
                    rice held by the Thai Government free to the Allies. Inasmuch as rice is greatly
                    needed by the Allies for other areas in the Far East and as Thailand in fact did
                    not participate actively against the Japanese or suffer very much from the war,
                    I thought personally that such a gift would be a gesture which might pay
                    dividends to Thailand far in excess of the monetary loss.</p>
            </div>
